    {
      "name": "Classic Jiangnan-Style Red Braised Pork (Hong Shao Rou)",
      "instructions": [
        "Cut the pork belly into 2cm cubes. Blanch in a pot of cold water with a few slices of ginger and a splash of Shaoxing rice wine. Bring to a boil, skim the scum, boil for 3-4 minutes, then drain and rinse with warm water.",
        "In a clean wok, add the pork belly over low-medium heat without adding oil. Sear the pork belly to render out some of the excess fat, turning occasionally until lightly golden on all sides. Remove the pork belly, leaving about 1 tablespoon of rendered fat in the wok.",
        "Add the rock sugar to the rendered pork fat. Melt over low heat, stirring constantly, until it turns a light amber syrup (caramelize).",
        "Immediately return the pork belly to the wok, stirring quickly to coat each piece evenly with the caramelized sugar.",
        "Add the remaining ginger, crushed garlic cloves, star anise, and scallions. Stir-fry for 1 minute until fragrant.",
        "Pour in the Shaoxing rice wine, light soy sauce, dark soy sauce, and enough boiling water to just cover the pork belly.",
        "Bring to a boil, then cover and simmer on low heat for 50 to 60 minutes until the pork is tender and the fat is melt-in-the-mouth.",
        "Uncover the wok, remove the ginger, garlic, and scallions. Turn the heat to high and stir constantly to reduce the sauce until it is thick, glossy, and coats the pork belly beautifully."
      ],
